I’m looking for a good CAD course. All the courses I’ve found have felt advanced. Even onshape’s CAD tutorial felt confusing. So I’m looking for something super simple to learn the basics. And it doesn’t have to be FRC based, this is for combat robotics mainly.

as silly as it sounds. the only way to start. is to start. open up your program start a sketch and just start placing things and extruding. once you get something that looks similar to what you have in mind, find someone to check your work after and offer constructive tips to learn even faster.

That being said, the 3005 curriculum on Onshape4FRC.com starts at THE very basics of both mechanical design and CAD in general.
Team Spyder has a bunch of resources as well that I love and get into every single detail you will ever need to know.

Spoken from someone who had to relearn a different CAD software for employment after using Solidworks for four years, the best way to learn is to follow a tutorial of some random part.

My favorite is this dude called “cad cam tutorial,” a ton of videos, some more beginner than others, but they teach pretty effectively just from following along.

Britt:

as silly as it sounds. the only way to start. is to start. open up your program start a sketch and just start placing things and extruding. once you get something that looks similar to what you have in mind, find someone to check your work after and offer constructive tips to learn even faster.

I completely agree with this as I first learned to CAD this way as well. This is also how we on 816 tend to end up teaching people if they didn’t come from our school’s engineering program that teaches CAD (Really just the exact same thing but just with Solidprofessor lessons as a start before it). I will always recommend this method for learning CAD, but there are resources that have been linked above that may be useful for you.

For Onshape, I watched quite literally the first three videos here:

And that’s served quite well for designing 150g to 250lb combat robots, and FRC robots.

Some of the few things I didn’t realize from these first three (no idea if they are covered later), is you definitely want to use mates in assembly, and please, if you need a screw, just “Standard Content” and “Hole” instead of importing from McMaster and using a bunch of fiddly chamfers and extrusions to countersink.
